<p class="drop-cap">Between 325 and 787, the undivided Church convened seven great councils. Each one responded to a crisis. Each one clarified something essential about who Christ is, what salvation means, and how Christians worship. These were not academic conferences. Bishops traveled weeks by horseback or ship. Emperors intervened. Tempers flared. People were exiled. The stakes were ultimate: get the theology wrong, and the entire structure of Christian hope collapses.</p>

<p>The Eastern Churches call these the "Seven Ecumenical Councils" and regard their definitions as irreformable. Not because bishops are infallible, but because the Holy Spirit, working through the consensus of the whole Church, protected these particular decisions from error. Understanding the councils is understanding the grammar of Christian faith.</p>

<h2>Nicaea I (325): Is the Son God?</h2>

<p>A priest in Alexandria named Arius taught that the Son of God was a creature. Exalted, first-created, godlike — but not God. "There was a time when He was not," Arius said.</p>

<p>Emperor Constantine, newly converted and alarmed by a Church tearing itself apart, summoned bishops to the city of Nicaea. Around 318 came. The council's answer was blunt: the Son is <em>homoousios</em> — "of one substance" — with the Father. Not similar. Not analogous. The same divine reality. The Nicene Creed, still recited in every liturgy, was born here.</p>

<p>Arius lost. But Arianism did not die at Nicaea. It took another sixty years of political turmoil, imperial flip-flopping, and the theological genius of the Cappadocian Fathers to settle the question for good.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— The Nicene Creed, 325 / 381">
  Light from Light, true God from true God, begotten not made, of one substance with the Father.
</Pullquote>

<h2>Constantinople I (381): And the Holy Spirit?</h2>

<p>If the Son is God, what about the Spirit? A group called the Pneumatomachoi ("Spirit-fighters") said the Spirit was a creature, a servant, a force — anything but divine. The council at Constantinople settled it. The Creed was expanded: the Spirit "proceeds from the Father," is "worshipped and glorified" together with Father and Son, and "spoke through the prophets."</p>

<p>This is the Creed as the Eastern Churches still confess it. The later Western addition of "and the Son" (the <em>filioque</em>) was not part of this council's decision — a fact that would become enormously consequential.</p>

<h2>Ephesus (431): Can Mary Be Called "Mother of God"?</h2>

<p>Nestorius, Patriarch of Constantinople, refused to call Mary <em>Theotokos</em> — "God-bearer" or "Mother of God." He preferred <em>Christotokos</em>: mother of Christ. The distinction sounds pedantic. It was not.</p>

<p>If Mary bore only the human nature of Christ, then Christ's humanity and divinity are separable. Two persons wearing one suit. The council at Ephesus, led fiercely by Cyril of Alexandria, declared: Mary is Theotokos because the child she bore is one person, and that person is God. The title protects Christology, not Mariology. It says something about Christ first and about Mary second.</p>

