<h2>Chalcedon (451): One Person, Two Natures</h2>

<p>The christological question came to a head at Chalcedon. If Christ is truly God and truly human, how do those two natures relate? Eutyches taught that the two natures merged into one — the human absorbed into the divine like a drop of wine in the ocean. The council rejected this. It also rejected Nestorius's separation.</p>

<p>The Chalcedonian Definition declared that Christ exists "in two natures, without confusion, without change, without division, without separation." Four negatives. The council told the Church what not to say rather than constructing a tidy philosophical system. The mystery remains. But the guardrails are clear.</p>

<p>Chalcedon split the Church. The Oriental Orthodox (Coptic, Armenian, Syriac, Ethiopian) rejected its language, though modern dialogue has shown the disagreement may have been more verbal than substantive. The wound is still healing.</p>

<h2>Constantinople II (553): Cleaning Up</h2>

<p>Emperor Justinian convened this council partly to reconcile the opponents of Chalcedon by condemning three theologians (the "Three Chapters") whose writings seemed too Nestorian. The politics were messy. Pope Vigilius was in Constantinople, under imperial pressure, and his relationship with the council was contentious.</p>

<p>The theological contribution: a stronger emphasis on the unity of Christ's person. The <em>Theopaschite formula</em> — "one of the Trinity suffered in the flesh" — was affirmed. God did not merely watch the Crucifixion from a safe distance. God experienced it.</p>

<h2>Constantinople III (680–681): Does Christ Have a Human Will?</h2>

<p>The Monothelites said Christ had only one will: the divine will. This seemed to simplify things. It actually gutted the Incarnation. If Christ has no human will, His humanity is incomplete. He did not struggle in Gethsemane. He did not choose obedience. He was a puppet.</p>

<p>The council declared two wills in Christ, divine and human, operating in harmony without conflict. The human will freely submits to the divine will — not by compulsion, but by love. This matters for theosis: if Christ's human will was real, then human will can genuinely cooperate with God. Freedom is not abolished by grace. It is fulfilled.</p>

<h2>Nicaea II (787): The Icons</h2>

<p>The Iconoclast emperors had spent decades smashing icons, whitewashing churches, and persecuting icon-venerators. The theological argument: icons of Christ violate the commandment against graven images. They are idolatry.</p>

<p>Nicaea II answered with a distinction and a christological argument. The distinction: <em>latreia</em> (worship) belongs to God alone; <em>proskynesis</em> (veneration, honor) may be given to icons, the Cross, the saints, and the relics. Venerating an icon is not worshipping the wood and paint. The honor passes to the person depicted.</p>

<p>The christological argument: because God became visible in Christ, Christ can be depicted. To forbid images of Christ is to deny the Incarnation. If God took on flesh, that flesh can be painted. The icon is a witness to the reality of the Incarnation.</p>

<p>Nicaea II closed the age of the councils. The icon had been vindicated. Every year, on the first Sunday of Great Lent, the Eastern Churches celebrate the "Triumph of Orthodoxy" — a feast commemorating this victory.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— St. John of Damascus, On the Divine Images, 8th century">
  I do not worship matter. I worship the Creator of matter, who became matter for my sake.
</Pullquote>

<h2>Why They Still Matter</h2>

<p>These seven councils built the doctrinal architecture that Eastern and Western Christians still inhabit. The Creed recited at every Divine Liturgy is their product. The icons on the iconostasis are their vindication. The theological vocabulary used in every seminary and catechism class — <em>homoousios</em>, <em>Theotokos</em>, two natures, two wills — was forged in these debates.</p>

<p>More than that, the councils established a model for how the Church resolves disputes: not by papal decree alone, not by individual theologians, but by the gathered bishops of the whole Church, guided (the East believes) by the Holy Spirit. This conciliar model remains the Eastern understanding of authority. The Church is not a monarchy. It is a communion.</p>

<h2>Further Reading</h2>

<p>For accessible introductions, start with Kallistos Ware's <em>The Orthodox Church</em> (chapters on the early councils) or Jaroslav Pelikan's <em>The Christian Tradition, Vol. 1: The Emergence of the Catholic Tradition</em>. For the Chalcedonian debates specifically, John Meyendorff's <em>Christ in Eastern Christian Thought</em> remains essential. Leo Donald Davis's <em>The First Seven Ecumenical Councils</em> provides a readable, council-by-council narrative.</p>

